Steps to Contribute:
Familiarize with the Repository: Visit the GitHub repository at https://github.com/alex/what-happens-when. Understand its content and structure to see where your contribution would fit best.
Identify Contribution Area: Look for sections where you can add substantial information. This could be an enhancement of existing content, addition of a new section, or clarification of complex concepts.
Fork and Clone: Fork the repository and clone it to your local machine.
Make Changes: Create a new branch in your fork and make your changes in this branch.
Commit and Push: Commit your changes with a clear message and push them to your fork.
Create Pull Request: Go to the original repository and create a pull request from your branch. Ensure your pull request description clearly states the value of your contribution.
Follow Up: Respond to any comments or requests for changes from repository maintainers.
Submission:
Share the pull request URL in your answer file and in the required field.
Note:
For Task 1, ensure your diagram is clear, accurate, and easy to understand.
For Task 2, your contribution should be meaningful and enhance the repository's content. Avoid trivial changes.
Both tasks provide a great opportunity to demonstrate your understanding of web technologies and contribute to the community. Once completed, you can include these in your portfolio or resume to showcase your skills and knowledge.